{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505849"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2491"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2491"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.07,0.03,0.5,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102014"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2491"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84464"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2995"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42505"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102014"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of increasing shortness of breath and fatigue. Last night he had severe night sweats.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes recently diagnosed gout, hypertension, and benign prostatic hyperplasia. His medications include allopurinol and amlodipine. He had transurethral resection of the prostate about 18 months ago. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 66/min, blood pressure 130/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is admitted to hospital and commenced on antibiotics. He improves over the next two days and is stable, ready for discharge tomorrow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubsequently, he develops a widespread tender skin rash that spreads from the trunk to the limbs and covers about 35% of his body surface area. Over the next few hours, he develops blisters, worsening widespread redness and some oral mucosal involvement. There is loss of epidermal integrity on rubbing the skin gently.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be the cause of this patient\u0027s latter presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allopurinol","Mycoplasma pneumoniae lung infection","Aspirin","Staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome","Warfarin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Etoxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN)\u003C/strong\u003E. About 90% of TENs cases are associated with a medication. Medications that are associated with TEN include allopurinol, antibiotics (e.g sulfonamide, penicillin, cephalosporin), antipsychotics/antiepileptics (e.g. carbamazepine, dilantin, lamotrigine), and NSAIDs (e.g piroxicam). If TEN is suspected, it is important to document an accurate medication timeline and cease all possible culprit drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E has been reported to cause TEN in children, however it is unlikely to be the cause in this adult patient. \u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with TEN. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E has not ever been associated with TEN, but does cause warfarin induced skin necrosis, which appears initially as pain and purpura, and progresses to black skin necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcal scalded skin syndrome (SSSS)\u003C/strong\u003E can appear similar clinically; however, it mainly occurs in children and neonates caused by the release of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E epidermolytic toxins A and B. SSSS is an intraepidermal detachment pattern, as opposed to TEN which causes full-thickness epidermal detachment. The positive Nikolsky sign (where gentle rubbing of the skin causes epidermal detachment) is present in both TEN and SSSS, as well as other blistering conditions like Stevens\u2013Johnson syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medications are the most common cause of toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN).","Allopurinol is a common medication associated with toxic epidermal necrolysis.","Nikolsky sign (epidermal detachment with gentle rubbing) is characteristic of toxic epidermal necrolysis."],"references":["Schwartz, RA; McDonough, PH; Lee, BW (August 2013). \u0022Toxic epidermal necrolysis: Part I. Introduction, history, classification, clinical features, systemic manifestations, etiology, and immunopathogenesis\u0022. Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology. 69 (2): 173.e1\u201313, quiz 185\u20136. doi:10.1016/j.jaad.2013.05.003. PMID 23866878. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23866878/","Labib A, Milroy C. Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis. [Updated 2023 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK574530/","Perdig\u00e3o S, Alves AS, Nunes M, Sousa C, Barros N. Allopurinol-Induced Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis. Cureus. 2024 Jan 13;16(1):e52222. doi: 10.7759/cureus.52222. PMID: 38347997; PMCID: PMC10861211. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10861211/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84464"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2491"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84464"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-06T12:19:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-06T12:20:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2491"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102014"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical 